<DOC><DOCNO> AP890319-0095 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-89 2319EST</FILEID><FIRST>u i AM-Panama-Tutu     03-19 0324</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Panama-Tutu,0336</SECOND><HEAD>Tutu Says Western Countries Could End Apartheid</HEAD><BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Desmond Tutu, the Anglican archbishopof South Africa, said Sunday his country's racial policies wouldchange immediately if the United States and other Western nationsdemanded it.   Tutu, who won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1984 for his activeopposition to South Africa's segregation policies known asapartheid, said his nation's racial policies are maintained becauseof ``immense economic interests'' by Western governments.   ``If the United States and the Western countries wanted,apartheid would end tomorrow,'' Tutu said at a news conference.   ``Some actions taken by the Western government have a backgroundof racism,'' Tutu told reporters. ``They say that dollars are moreimportant than people, especially when those people are black.''   Tutu and six other Anglican officials arrived in Panama Saturdayfrom Nicaragua, where they toured the country for five days. Theyleave Panama on Tuesday.   In Managua Saturday, the clerics issued a statement backing theleftist Sandinista government's recent reforms and called on theU.S. government to help resettle the 11,000 Nicaraguan rebels inHonduras.   An agreement signed Feb. 14 by five Central American presidentssought to disband the Nicaraguan rebels, known as Contras. TheContras have been supported by the U.S. government since 1981.   The Anglican officials are visiting at the invitation of the Rev.Sturdie Downs, bishop of Nicaragua's Episcopal Church.   Edmond Browning, Anglican primate in the United States, said heaccepted the invitation after hearing about ``the horrible pain andsuffering of the people in these countries.''   The religious leaders were scheduled to meet Monday with Gen.Manuel Antonio Noriega, head of the nation's security forces.   The U.S. government imposed sanctions against Panama in April1988 to force the fall of Noriega, the country's de facto ruler. Acourt in Florida has indicted Noriega on charges of drug trafficking.   The U.S. sanctions have seriously damaged Panama's economy.</TEXT></DOC>